LEADERS of the EFF have opened a case against finance minister Malusi Gigaba at the Jo'burg central police station today.Led by their CIC Julius Malema, the red berets opened charges against Gigaba and others whom they accuse of being at the centre of corruption in the procurement of diesel locomotives by Transnet. "We have opened a case against Zuma, Gigaba and others who stole R17 billion from Transnet," said Malema.Malema said on Thursday at a press conference that whistle-blowers at Transnet provided them with information that Gigaba and other senior Transnet officials have been favouring the Gupta family in state tenders. Malema: we bought 1 unit of a locomotive for R42m. No country in the world has ever bought a locomotive for that much, not even in rich ones&mdash; EFF Official Account (@EFFSouthAfrica) June 9, 2017Malema: police never do anything about cases we open against Zuma because they too are captured and report to the Guptas&mdash; EFF Official Account (@EFFSouthAfrica) June 9, 2017EFF CIC @Julius_S_Malema and the leadership now at Joburg Central Police Station to lay charges against Gigaba et.al. #TransnetCorruption pic.twitter.com/3mrgsp3KEF&mdash; EFF Official Account (@EFFSouthAfrica) June 9, 2017Malema: We have opened a case against Zuma, Gigaba &amp; Gupta crooks who stole R17b in Transnet pic.twitter.com/i1DatQ3xmH&mdash; EFF Official Account (@EFFSouthAfrica) June 9, 2017CIC @Julius_S_Malema and EFF Officials laying charges against Gigaba and others at Joburg Central Police Station #TransnetCorruption pic.twitter.com/gln1wn8lpq&mdash; EFF Official Account (@EFFSouthAfrica) June 9, 2017